command-line args

primer, ch.11

int main(int argc, char **argv)
    - char **argv == char *argv[]

C compilers allow main() to have no args or else to have 2 args
    - 1st arg (argc): num of strings in the command-line (argument count)
        - system uses space to tell when on string ends and the next begins
    - 2nd arg (argv): array of pointers to adresses of each string (argument values)
        - argv[0]: name of the program itself

EXAMPLE
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    printf("The command line has %d arguments:\n", argc - 1);
    for (int count = 1; count < argc; count++)
        printf("%d: %s\n", count, argv[count]);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
// The command line has 2 arguments:
// 1: joe
// 2: doe
